 * 
 * Why is heapInt address different than the other 3 memory addresses?
 * All of the addresses point to different variables.
 * 
 * Why are the other 3 memory addresses output the same?
 * The variables that they all point to are the same location, just defined to different names
 * 
 * What is the result of modifying the value of the ptrToStack variable?
 * it changes the original stackint variable.
 * 
 * What is the result of modifying the value of the refToStack variable?
 * it also changes the original stackint variable.
 */

INIT GRADE: 7.5/10

Instructor Response:

"Good work. Numbers 1 and 3 read incorrect to me. The reason heapInt has a different 
memory address than the other 3 is because it is dynamically allocated with the new 
keyword and is stored on the heap. The other 3 are automatically allocated, meaning 
not allocated with the new keyword, so they are stored on the stack. Number 3 is 
worded purposefully to test if students remember the "value" stored in a pointer, 
which is a memory address. When we change the value of a pointer, you are changing 
to a different memory address. This change in value would not affect stackInt at all, 
instead ptrToStack would simply point to something else."